: 147<br> <font color=#333333>(12/16/02 9:48:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=417.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://personal.atl.bellsouth.net/atl/d/a/dastorys/Pictures/Nec-60x60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   To Balance damage dealers within the game, my view.</span><hr size=1> While I'll probably be shot down, I've been reading a bit on the various class boards, and have come to some ideas on the damage balance within the game.  Especially after having visited the Safehouse a few times, I thought I'd like hear the opinions of the other classes who rightly or not feel they should be the masters of damage.<br>
<br>
First, I guess I should clarify who exactly I feel is a damage class.  I see there being 2 ranks of damage dealer, those who specialize in damage, and a less damaging, though more utilitarian rank behind the heavy hitters.  I see each rank as being 3 classes, as there are 6 spots in a group, and to be equal, there needs to be 2 to 3 viable possibilities for each spot.  I see the following as the spots in a well constructed group, and believe that each should be balanced with the others in their position:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Heavy Hitters:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Wizards<br>
Magicians<br>
Rogues<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Healers:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Clerics<br>
Shaman<br>
Druid<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Second String Damage/Utility:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Monks<br>
Beastlords<br>
Rangers<br>
Necromancers<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Tanks:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Warriors<br>
Paladins<br>
Shadowknights<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Crowd Control:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Bards<br>
Enchanters<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Buffs/Debuffs:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Many of the classes fall back on this, and more probably should.  All of the second string damage classes should have a significant contribution here, with the probable exception of monks, who provide their second role as pullers and secondary tanks, though that has changed since the recent downgrades of monk defense—they are kind of hard to place now.  I don’t feel that any class should primarily be a buffing class however, as it’s generally not much fun in and of itself.  Some classes are too powerful here, considering their power in another primary grouping role.  Debuffs I fit in here too, as they should improve the performance by allowing spells to land better, making the mob easier to hit, etc.  <br>
<br>
Now on to my ideas of Damage Balance.<br>
<br>
It’s my belief that the top 3 damage classes should do the same DPS when equally leveled and equipped.  This means that when a group says ‘we need a damage dealer’ they look for these classes first, with the second rank being considered if one of their utility roles are also lacking or would help the party function.<br>
<br>
As this relates to Rogues, Wizards and Mages, I have this vision.  Fights that favor neither Spell Damage, nor melee damage should see them on equal footing.  Fights that favor melee damage, either through extreme hitpoints, spell immunities, extreme resists, or spells/effects that prevent casting should favor rogues somewhat, with Mages being reduced, and Wizards lagging behind.  Obviously, the reverse situation is true if the mob favors casting damage through low Hitpoints, High AC, very low resists, or effects that hamper melee such as Slow or Attack Debuffs.  Mages, as they do both melee through pets, and cast spells should rarely find themselves completely disadvantaged, though in many cases they will find they are not optimal either, except in cases where elementals are the preferred tanks due to the nature of the mob, the mob hits extremely fast or can’t be slowed bringing the DS to the fore, etc...<br>
<br>
To balance this, there needs to be a balance of both the extreme damage capability of the classes, and their somewhat limited utility to a group.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Rogues.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Even if you equally balance the damage a rogue can do with a  wizard or a magician, there is no question they will, as all melee, lag in utility—and be less desireable in a group than virtually anyone because of it.<br>
Poisons and their Skills are the answer.<br>
<br>
--<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sneak/Hide</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- this could be made more valuable if there was a short term, fairly reusable AA to allow the user to be undetected by even see-invis mobs.  Thus, their scouting ability is improved<br>
--<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Detect Traps</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- This ability should be constant once in use like Sneak, slowing the movement rate of the rogue, and giving Tracking style updates with each tick, possibly even causing a small particle effect to highlight any detected traps.<br>
--<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Disarm Traps</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- this should come in 3 stages.  Early on, it acts similar to hide, so that a detected trap is off so long as a rogue is near and unmoving, holding the trap deactivated till the party passes, and a few seconds after he lets go (think trap only mez, based on the skill, with skill dependant memblur).  As a later upgrade, the rogue should himself be immune to detected traps, passing them freely, enhancing his scouting role. As the final upgrade, the immunity should be granted to all nearby groupmates, allowing skilled parties to bypass the traps all together.<br>
--<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Poisons</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- The problem with poisons is that they are extreme effort to little reward propositions.  Offering a small selection of poisons on vendors at decent prices would help.  Secondly, not all poisons should be on weapons.  I could suggest a narcotic, which acts as a harmony on a right click potion style item, to aid the rogue in pulling- this would be more worth the effort involved in most poisons.  I’d also suggest poisons that emphasize the rogues stealth skills, like a Mob equipable item that has 30% slow or snare that forces the rogue to sneak up behind the mob and give it to him, or an item that is –200hp equipable only by mobs, with stronger versions being usable in more slots with a cap of say 1000hp for multiple ‘doses’.  Again, think of the time, money, and effort required to master this rogue unique skill, and find a way to implement it so that it reinforces the idea of stealthy guy instead of walking flechette cannon.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Mages</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
While dealing damage is great, certain utility is demanded of a casting class, and I feel, Mages seriously lack in this department, while being slightly overpowered in damage output—relatively.  While I believe that Firebolt of Tallon should properly be about a 1600 damage spell with a 4’ish damage ratio to be properly balanced against the high level wizard spells, there are many schools of thought on the damage issue.<br>
<br>
--<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Summons</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- For a class based on their ability to summon items, mages sure got the shaft.  No summoned items, in general, are worth the time it takes to memorize the spell.  The Weightless bags, and Focus items being the exceptions.  Other than these, anything else the mage can summon is generally available at vendors all over norrath, reducing the utility value from what could have been tremendous, to nearly nil.  And then there’s the pets, which do rock, but a few other classes’ pets come very close to the power, if not the variety of the elementals, which I think could be tolerated a bit more if the other summonses weren’t so useless.  <br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Bane Weapons</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- it would be nice if a spell could be quested for at least the high level Seru/Shissar bane weapons only equipable by pets.  Also, melee equippable weapons with Vampyre bane, elemental bane, and possibly humanoid bane with decent level appropriate ratios could also be quested spells—not the ratio of fine steel for our post Luclin casters please.<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Ranged Weapons</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- one of the few items actually requested of mages, and while a low level conjure might be a throwing knife or shuriken, High level mages should be able to summon:Frisbee(stack of long range, low damage pulling tool),and Summon:Mage Bolt (Short Range, Good Damage arrows), possibly with +range skill % to improve accuracy over store bought items, perhaps the extra damage could work as + magic/fire bane style damage, so it could be resisted.<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Summoned Items as Buffs</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->- Summoned cloth armor with flowing thought values equivalent to the clarity line (equivalent in function, if not value), Summoned Fungus item with fungal regrowth on it, Summoned items with ATTK buffs on it, items with +75 to selected resists to match the buffs of other classes.  Things that people will ask for if grouped with a mage, the days where cold stones, water stones and rings of flight are the only useful summons should have been dead in Kunark.<br>
Some ideas could be new spells, others would probably be best if the appropriate spells were simply upgraded, but the mage summoned items need serious reconsideration.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Wizards</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I believe that wizards are the most balanced of the Heavy Hitters at the moment, since with Evac, Stun and Snare they suffer less from lack of utility than either Rogues or Magicians.  What they do lack, that EVERY other class has, is infinitely sustainable damage of some kind, unless you count Xuzl.  Perhaps the greatest lack the wizard has is of the EQ’s community opinion that wizards make poor groupies because of a lack of contribution to a group effort.  I offer 2 suggestions to correct this situation:<br>
<br>
--<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Recharge Nukes</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->-A large inefficient nuke, that over 30 seconds returns the mana spent on it as a recourse effect.  The DPS on this nuke should be 75% of the low-end damage that the pets provide to the Mages, with critical blasts bringing it in line with the 75% DPS of the high end pets on average.  This would give us our sustainable damage, with the ability to bring our burst damage to bear as needed.  Since it’s magical damage and limited by resists and magic immune mobs, Mages remain on the Melee/Magic edge, Rogues rule melee, and Wizards rule pure magic.<br>
-- <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A Group usable buff</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> that adds Elemental Procs and Bane damage to the melee.  Also, in line with Wizard abilities it would be nice if Wizards could cast a ‘critical buff’  that would add/increase the chances of critical strikes and blast—preferably a high enough amount to be easily noticeable by those under it’s effects, around 15 to 20%.<br>
<br>
<br>
As an end note on my views of the balance of damage output.  Necromancers should probably replace Wizards or Mages on some fights in the ranks of the heavy hitters, especially those fights that last a long time, or where Fire/Magic resist is high, and Disease/Poison is not. <br>
<br>
Also, I have no problem with AM3 rangers outdamaging everyone for a short time based on their skills, though I do take a slight bit offense at this being without danger or cost to the ranger.  Having very low agro on archery is the reason it was made useless for most levels in the first place, as it was non-mana limited, ranged damage, and thus deemed too low a risk for it to be a viable damage tool.  I would suggest that the extreme damage arrows that make the huge DPS numbers possible be flagged as Magic Items, and that Endless Quiver work only on Non-magic arrows, thus they don’t stick a single ICBM on the bow, outdamage god and everyone else with it at low/no risk, then put It away till the next time.  This is a bit exaggerated, I know, but there should be more cost to being on top of the damage heap.<br>
 <p><br>
